I pulled up your codex/SKILL.md on feat/typescript-migration-2.

Here’s a review of what you’ve got, what’s professional/useful, and what I’d tweak.

What’s strong (professional + useful)

Clear “authoritative workflow” intent: it’s unambiguous that the agent must follow this file for sprint work. That’s good process control.

State machine approach with codex/current-sprint + codex/current-phase and a fixed set of phases/status values is exactly what makes Codex/agent work predictable and auditable.

Good repo-specific conventions: sprint folder location, doc names, one sprint = one branch, incremental commits, and recording validation results in PR.md. This is genuinely “real world professional” for keeping migration work safe.

Validation rules are targeted (typecheck, tests, build:typed, plus manual runtime checks) and explicitly require recording results. That’s a strong quality bar.

TS-first extraction guidance (“business logic in ts/core/*, runtime boundaries in src/*.gs”) matches your migration strategy and reduces tech debt.

What I’d fix / tighten (small but important)
1) Formatting/metadata header is malformed

Your frontmatter looks like it got collapsed into one line:
--- name: sprint-loop description: ... ---
If anything is consuming YAML frontmatter, it likely expects:

---
name: sprint-loop
description: ...
---

Even if nothing parses it, clean formatting makes it easier to maintain.

2) Sprint ID format has a dangling underscore

You wrote: YYYY-MM-DD_feat_
That trailing underscore will create awkward IDs and paths. Consider:

YYYY-MM-DD_feat_<slug> (best)

or YYYY-MM-DD_feat-<slug>

Right now you also say the agent must derive a slug, but the sprint-id example doesn’t include it.

3) Branch folder path uses placeholders but doesn’t show the concrete example

You reference codex/branch// in multiple places.
I’d make this explicit as:
codex/branch/<sprint-id>/
So there’s no ambiguity for the agent (and no accidental double slashes).

4) Add one “migration-specific” rule for generated output

Because you generate B08_TypedBudget.generated.gs, it’s worth adding a single line like:

“Never hand-edit generated files; changes must come from TS build pipeline.”

That’s a classic tech-debt trap during migrations.

5) Add an explicit “fixture policy”

Since you’re rolling out fixtures, add one small rule like:

“Behavior changes must be reflected by updating/adding fixtures; migrations should prefer parity/fixture confirmation.”

This keeps “stability into main” aligned with your stated goal.

What’s “not so useful” (or could be shorter)

The templates are fine, but the file is very dense. Once stable, consider moving the templates into separate files (or keep them but collapse them under a “Templates” section as you did—already decent).

Bottom line

This is a good, professional “agent operating procedure” for a migration repo. It’s already doing the right things: enforce phases, force evidence, constrain scope. The main improvements are clarity + removing ambiguity (frontmatter formatting, sprint-id including slug, and explicit paths).

If you want, I can rewrite SKILL.md into a cleaner v2 (same rules, clearer formatting, with the 2–3 extra migration rules above) and keep it drop-in compatible with your current process.